Innitial Commit of rough prototype
Added coment to check it works

Began cleanup of prototype. Removed previous inaccurate summary system, and added as subjects the location,person,and organisation. Result now has a list of subjects and dates, to later analyse to produce proper dates and subjects.
Added cleanup method, that removes starting commas from the tree
Added documentation, and attempted to add method to delete dates (does't work)
TestClass.java: -added TODO

Token: -removed as its not used.
Tree: -removed as its not used.
TreeNode: -removed as its not used.

Engine.java: -refactored the code in TestClass.java to Engine.java -added initial documentation and comments -getResults() will return a list of Result objects based on the input text, that will be used later to produce a timeline of events
Engine.java: -added TODO for later work
Engine.java: -added TODO for later work

Engine.java: -added class-level documentation -removed setting grammatical subjects, as it was sometimes giving double subjects; should make subject list in Result be a set to avoid having duplicates.
TestClass.java: -commented out the call and print of Results that was obtained from code in the TestClass, as now the Engine is used for that.
Engine.java: -uncommented setGrammaticalSubjects()

Engine.java: -added the print of the work done by the annotator for development purpose of removing time expressions -made threshold non-final as we need to modify for a partial solution to remove time expressions -added method removeTimeExpressions() that removes time expressions from the tree, to trim it down -removeTimeExpressions() sets the threshold to 0 to remove any XP before the NP and calls xpBeforeNP, which if its a time expressions will be a PP (eg On the Friday...).Then sets the threshold back to its original value. -Added comments to removeTimeExpressions() for possible ways to remove time expressions.
Engine.java: -added partial documentation for removeTimeExpressions() -added a comment for other possible way to remove time expressions
Engine.java: - Got the normalized entity tag, the suggested date by the stanford corenlp

Engine.java: - tried to delete the temporal expressions in the sentence when we are using named entity recognition, but was then left with the issue that deleting leftover "On..."(having tag IN, first child of a PP) would also delete other PPs that had as there first child IN but didnt previously hold a date so the sentence would no longer make grammatical sense. -made setDatesAndSubjectsNET return a String now to deal with the attempt of removing temporal expressions

Engine.java: - made setDatesAndSubjectsNET be void again. - removed from setDatesAndSubjects string that previously was supposed to not contain time expressions, and the prints of it that were used to debug.

Engine.java: -changed produceString to not add a space after the last word in the returned String. -for removeTimeExpressions() began implementing the removal of time expressions according to Hedge Trimmer: A Parse-and-Trim Approach to Headline Generation document. First deleting any PPs that contain a NP which itself has the time expression.(next: delete any NP that contains the time expression).

Engine.java: -added the implementation in removeTimeExpressions to delete any NP that contains a time expression. (In the future will try to combine the two for a better solution). -removed the previous implementation of removeTimeExpressions that would delete any XP before NP in the tree, but this would delete most of the time any time expression, but it could delete non time expressions that are also XP and appear before the NP (subject) of the sentence.
Engine.java: -added print statements of the tree before going through removeTimeExpressions and afterwards. (Commented out the print in the middle)
Added gitignore file to ignore workspace
Merged feature_remove-time-expressions into master branch
Engine.java: -changed the way the leftmostLowest S is picked, using postorder.

Engine.java: -getResults(input, date) added in String date, as a reference date for the normalized entity date tags. -removed print statements in for loops.
TestClass.java: -passed in a date into the Engine.getResults() call.

Result.java: -changed subjects to a set from a list.
Engine.java: -commented out setting the Grammatical subject as it was adding subjects like "that" (need to filter subjects added in)

Result.java: -added documentation and referencing. -formatted the code (spacing added). -removed else statement that returns in XpOverXP, as it wasn't needed, method ends anyways if it doesn't enter the if for the recursive call.
Merged feature_determine-dates-exactly into master
First commit for develop
First commit for develop

Engine.java: -storing the normalized date in the result object
Result.java: -added addDate_1() which needs to be implemented to parse dates into Date objects. Just prints them out at the moment.

TestClass.java: - added two more sentences to see how StanfordCoreNLP processes references to last month and last week.
Result.java: -added comment for future built system to parse strings into dates.
TimelineDate.java: -will be used to parse the String dates given by StanfordCoreNLP to actual dates to then use in the timeline. -wrote pseudo-code for parse() (in comments)

TimelineDate.java: -added the efficient way of compiling patterns when they are going to be reused (being static and final). -started implementing the pseudo-code. Checks if the given input starts with YYYY or YYYX or YYXX or YXXX.
Engine.java: -tested if for the dates found in the pre-defined text (which always have some form of start year), matches with the regex in TimelineDate (it does!).
TestClass.java: -commented out code to test the pattern matching for the date

Engine.java: -calling TimelineDate.parse() to see how our date extraction system is working with the normalized dates provided by the StanfordCoreNLP
TestClass.java: -added an extra sentence to see how the StanfordCoreNLP gives normalized dates for when an event is repeated every year on a certain month.
TimelineDate.java: -added the Patterns for the different formats found up to now for the Normalized Dates provided by the StanfordCoreNLP. Identifies just years, years and months (even with the years that are unspecified), years,months and days, years and week number, years and season. -added comments for format when years are unknown but month is: where the text is of the type XXXX-MM INTERSECT P1Y.

TimelineData.java: -added comments for further parsing of possible ouputs of StanfordCoreNLP, ie XXXX-MM INTERSECT PX[Y/M/W/D] ( every [Y/M/W/D] in M ...)
TestClass.java: -added an extra sentence to see how the StanfordCoreNLP gives normalized dates for when an event is repeated every day/week/month/year on a certain month.

TimelineDate.java: -added getDate() method that will for every date in the range passed into parse (which can be just 1) produce a list of dates (at most size 2) that represent that date: i.e. if have a range of a dates than the list will contain 2 dates, else will contain 1. -added comments to getDate() to explain the process of producing each date for each of the matching cases. -added comments to parse to define what to do in the case the date format includes INTERSECT PX[YMDW]. Two choices: calculate the date passed along with INTERSECT... independently and just normalize INTERSECT... to a string that will be shown next to the date (most likely to work), or create a range representing the date and INTERSECT...(less likely to work). -added TODO of possible way to implement getDate which is to split it into methods to get year, month, day (returns the default values if not possible), and develop case when the month is known but not the year: XXXX-mm

Engine.java: -the TimelineDate.parse() has been moved to the Result class such that the Engine just passes the normalized date to the Result which will then turn it to a Date object.
Result.java: -initialized the date arraylist, added getter and setter methods for it (to test output), and parses the date passed into addDate_1 into TimelineDate to receive an arraylist of dates for the result.
TestClass.java: -added prints to see the dates stored for each result after going through the TimelineDate parser.
TimelineDate.java: -added map to hold the months for each season in UK. -parseDate now returns a list of dates, which is of size 1 if only one date is identified or of size 2 if a range is identified. -the list is split and passed into the (future) recursive method. -getDate identifies the known normalized patterns for dates and breaks and assigns default values where necessary to later produce a date object, which is added to the list. -TODO: break of INTERSECT... from normalized dates (e.g. DATE INTERSECT....) to process the date in getDate and pass on the INTERSECT as additional information. -TODO: definitely requires refactoring and optimization

TimelineDate.java: -a year pattern can now also just be: XXXX (completely unknown date with range 0000-9999). -if the string date is of format DATE INTERSECT.., it will split it to get DATE and process DATE separately. (Later would process INTERSECT.. to pass in as additional information with the date retrieved: e.g. 2014-01-01 -> 2016-01-01 every 2 days for 2014/2016 INTERSECT P2D. -prints added for clarity
TimelineDate.java: -optimised imports -removed commented out code -added method stub for cleanup() that cleans the arraylist of dates to have at most two

TimelineDate.java: -correctly produces a list for all known date formats produced by StanfordCoreNLP. -Made the hashmap of season hold the string representation of the start and end month of each season. -added the patterns that consider each part of a date individually. -parse() now splits the date into the actual date information (e.g. YYYY-MM-DD) and the additional information (e.g. INTERSECT ...), to then process the date information independently. -getDate() know processes each part of a date (semi-) independently of each other. Breaking the input date into its parts, and evaluating each in a sequential order

Result.java: -fixed the constructor. -removed unused list of dates -toString now uses the timelinedate as the date of a result object. -results are now comparable by their timeline dates.
TimelineDate.java: -holds a start and end date ( both can be null), and the string that set these dates. -parse doesn't return a list anymore as TimelineDate is now responsible for holding the dates. -enforceRules() ensures that TimelineDate holds the min date and max date up to now, after having processed a date String. -sortList() is used to sort the resulting list of parse() to then get its min and max to compare to the min max of TimelineDate, to then update appropriately. -toString() prints the range of dates accordingly, only prints one if we don't have a second date. -compareTo() compares this TimelineDate with another, by just comparing the start date, i.e. in the timeline, if your start date is before another you will appear first (even in the other finishes first).
TestClass.java: -tested out the sorting for the given input text, it works.

TestClass.java: -removed the previous implementation of the Engine, that was unused, and just there for testing purposes.
TimelineDate.java: -optimised imports. -added documentation. -formatted code.
Result.java: -formatted the code. -added documentation.
